Here’s what happens now. When the game is over (i.e., when you hit an object), Runner.prototype.gameOver() is called and the action is triggered.
In this case, you’ll hear a sound, the game stops, and a Game Over message appears. That’s without our code.
What our code does is replaces the gameOver function with an empty function. 
That means that instead of hearing the sound, the game stopping, and the message appearing, nothing happens. You just keep running.
